-- Persian Gulf Stocks: Al-Ahsa, Banque Saudi Fransi, Saudi Kayan
-- B y   Z a h r a   H a n k i r
-- 2012-01-17T13:43:25Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-17/persian-gulf-stocks-ezdan-real-estate-sorouh-and-dana-gas.html
Dubai’s  shares  rose 0.7 percent, the
most this month, to 1,310.40 at the 2 p.m. close in the emirate.
Qatar’s  QE Index (DSM)  slipped 0.5 percent and  Saudi Arabia ’s  Tadawul
All Share Index (SASEIDX)  declined 0.8 percent.  The following shares were active in the Persian Gulf
region. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Al-Ahsa Development Co. (AADC)   advanced the most in more
than two weeks, rising 5.1 percent to 14.55 riyals. The Saudi
Arabian investment company appointed Waleed Al-Afaleq as
chairman after Khalid Bin Omar Bin Al-Baltan quit.  Banque Saudi Fransi (BSFR)   declined the most in a month,
losing 1.2 percent to 41.5 riyals. The Saudi lender part-owned
by  Credit Agricole SA (ACA)  posted a 7 percent decline in fourth-
quarter profit to 661 million riyals ($176 million) as operating
expenses increased.  Kuwait Projects Co. (KPROJ)   rallied to the highest in
more than a month, gaining 1.6 percent to 315 fils. The
country’s biggest privately owned investment company is looking
to expand in  Turkey ’s financial services industry, Chief
Financial Officer Pinak Maitra said.  National Investments Co. (NINV)  (NINV KK) rose the most in a week,
advancing 2.5 percent to 164 fils. The Kuwaiti investment
company got approval to extend a 10 percent share buyback by six
months.  Saudi Kayan Petrochemical Co. (KAYAN)   slumped the most
in more than five months, losing 6.7 percent to 15.95 riyals.
The unit of  Saudi Basic Industries Corp. (SABIC)   said its
fourth-quarter loss widened. Saudi Basic shares dropped 2.1
percent to 92 riyals.  Sahara Petrochemical Co. (SPC)   dropped to the lowest
since March 6, tumbling 3.6 percent to 14.55 riyals. The Saudi
Arabian manufacturer of chemicals said fourth-quarter profit
fell 89 percent to 5 million riyals.  Saudi Ceramic (SCERCO)   retreated the most since Aug. 6,
slumping 2.7 percent to 145.5 riyals. The manufacturer and
retailer of ceramic products said fourth-quarter profit fell to
52.5 million riyals.  Sorouh Real Estate Co. (SOROUH)  ,  Abu Dhabi ’s second-
biggest property developer by market value, rose for the first
time in nine days, gaining 3 percent to 69 fils. The stock was
started with “buy” and a price estimate of 89 fils at Beltone
Financial. Excluding today, the shares slumped 21 percent so far
this year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
